{{Infobox person | name = Sheryl Underwood | image = Underwood, Sheryl (2008).jpg | caption = Underwood in 2008 | birth_name = Sheryl Patrice Underwood | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1963|10|28}} | birth_place = [[Little Rock, AR]], U.S. | nationality = American | party = [[Republican Party of the United States|Republican]] | occupation = {{hlist|[[Comedian]]|[[actress]]|[[Television presenter|television host]]}} | notable_works = {{hlist|[[The Talk (TV series)|''The Talk'']]|''BET Comic View''}} | module = {{infobox comedian|embed=yes | medium = {{hlist|Stand-up|television|film}} | active = 1988–present | subject = {{hlist|[[Human sexuality]]|[[race relations]]|[[African-American culture]]|[[politics]]}} | influences = {{hlist|[[Redd Foxx]]|[[Lawanda Page]]|[[Moms Mabley]]|[[Bernie Mac]]}} | education = [[University of Illinois at Chicago]] | website = [http://www.sherylunderwoodandfriends.com/ sherylunderwoodandfriends.com] }} }} '''Sheryl Patrice Underwood''' (born {{Birth date|1963|10|28|mf=y}})<ref name=tvg>{{cite web| url = http://www.tvguide.com/celebrities/sheryl-underwood/198766/| title=Sheryl Underwood| publisher=[[TV Guide|TVGuide.com]] | accessdate= June 4, 2015}}</ref> is an American comedian, actress and television host. She first rose to prominence in the comedy world as the first female finalist in 1989's Miller Lite Comedy Search. She is well known for hosting ''BET Comic View'' and is currently one of the five hosts on the daytime chat show ''[[The Talk (U.S. TV series)|The Talk]]'' on [[CBS]], a role she first stepped into in the autumn of 2011.
==Early life== Underwood was born in Little Rock, AR. Later,she moved to [[Atwater, California]] where she attended high school.<ref>[https://prezi.com/peybdjkmbdqz/sheryl-underwood/ Sheryl Underwood by Diana Gibbs on Prezi] Retrievesed 2016-11-27.</ref> She has a brother, Michael, and an older sister, Frankie, who was diagnosed with polio. Michael and Sheryl would often take turns giving care to Frankie. Sheryl is now Frankie's caretaker.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.monstersandcritics.com/smallscreen/the-talk-host-sheryl-underwood-on-life-caring-for-her-disabled-sister/|title=The Talk host Sheryl Underwood on life caring for her disabled sister|date=2016-09-15|newspaper=Monsters and Critics|language=en-US|access-date=2016-10-07}}</ref>
Underwood revealed that she was born with a twin that didn't survive. She went on to say that she had been lied to by her mother, who said that her father murdered her sister. Underwood admitted to carrying her sister's birth certificate around with her. She even stated that her mother stabbed her father, who survived, after Underwood had gotten close to her father, which her mother wanted to prevent after she lied to Underwood about her father being a murderer.
==Professional career== After graduating college, she served in the military.{{citation needed|date=June 2015}} She later gained public notice as the first female finalist in the [[Miller Lite Comedy Search]] in 1989.<ref name="MiamiImprov">{{cite web |url=http://www.symfonee.com/improv/miami/comedians/Bio.aspx?Uid=%7B5717c3da-1c60-40e9-a267-41ef19aa4652%7D |title=Sheryl Underwood |accessdate=2008-08-19 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081215161644/http://www.symfonee.com/improv/miami/comedians/Bio.aspx?Uid=%7B5717c3da-1c60-40e9-a267-41ef19aa4652%7D |archivedate=2008-12-15 |df= }}</ref> She won the BET "Funniest Female Comedian on Comic View" award in 1994 and the BET Comedy Awards' Platinum Mic Viewers Choice Award in 2005.<ref name="TV.com" />
Following her stand up success, Underwood took a number of minor acting roles including Bad Mouth Bessie in the 1998 film ''[[I Got the Hook Up]],'' and Catfish Rita in the 2005 film ''[[Beauty Shop]]''.
Underwood was the host of BET's ''Comic View'' and executive producer and host of the limited run comedy/variety series ''Holla'' (September 2002 – January 2003).<ref name="TV.com2">{{cite web|url=http://www.tv.com/holla/show/14481/summary.html|title=Holla|work=TV.com|publisher=CNET Networks, Inc.}}</ref> [[Image:Sheryl Underwood Kuwait.jpg|thumb|left|Sheryl Underwood with a soldier at Camp Arifjan, Kuwait, December 12, 2007 as a part of the Sgt. Maj. of the Army's Hope and Freedom tour to entertain deployed troops.]] [[File:The Ladies of TV 2012.jpg|thumb|''The Talk'' co-hosts [[Julie Chen]], [[Aisha Tyler]], [[Sharon Osbourne]], [[Sara Gilbert]] and Sheryl Underwood in 2012.]] Underwood was a contributor on the nationally syndicated ''[[Tom Joyner Morning Show]]'' until June 2010 when she jumped ship to ''[[The Steve Harvey Morning Show]]'' to be their contributor.<ref name="ZetaPress" /><ref>{{cite web|title=Underwood Jumps From Joyner To Harvey|url=http://www.bvnewswire.com/2010/07/14/sheryl-underwood-lebron-tom-joyner-steve-harvey|work=BV Newswire}}</ref> She briefly hosted her own radio program, ''Sheryl Underwood and Company'' for [[Radio One (company)|Radio One]]-owned Syndication One News/Talk and [[XM Satellite Radio]]'s Channel 169 (The Power ).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tv.com/tracking/viewer.html?sls_id=15947&ref_type=104&ref_id=153540&tag=updates;title;0 |title=Comedian Sheryl Underwood gets a daily talk show on XM |date=2007-03-26 |accessdate=2008-08-19 |work=ReddingNewsReview.com |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081212204650/http://www.tv.com/tracking/viewer.html?sls_id=15947&ref_type=104&ref_id=153540&tag=updates%3Btitle%3B0 |archivedate=2008-12-12 |df= }}</ref> On Tuesday nights, Underwood hosts ''The Sheryl Underwood Show'' on [[Jamie Foxx]]'s [[Sirius Satellite Radio]] channel, [[The Foxxhole]] (Sirius 106) <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sirius.com/thefoxxhole|title=The Foxxhole}}</ref>
In 2011, she joined the daytime show ''[[The Talk (U.S. TV series)|The Talk]]'' in its second season replacing [[Leah Remini]].
==Personal life== {{quote box |quote = I would call myself a sexually progressive, God-fearing, black Republican.|Sheryl Underwood|<ref name="TV.com" />}}
She holds a Bachelor of Arts degree in Liberal Arts from the [[University of Illinois at Chicago]] and master's degrees in Media Management and Mass Communication from [[Governors State University]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Sheryl Underwood ( Special Event)|url=http://palmbeachimprov.com/show_right.cfm?id=59589&cart|work=PalmBeachImprov.com|accessdate=30 October 2011}}</ref> Underwood once served in the U.S. Armed Forces, and frequently makes jokes about "all the creative places you can get busy on a military base."
Underwood is a lifelong [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newsone.com/3090539/newsone-now-exclusive-the-talks-sheryl-underwood-dishes-gop-politics-video/|title=NewsOne Now Exclusive: 'The Talk's' Sheryl Underwood Dishes GOP Politics [VIDEO]|date=10 February 2015|publisher=}}</ref> However she campaigned for [[Barack Obama]]'s re-election in [[United States presidential election, 2012]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://on.aol.com/video/why-proud-republican-sheryl-underwood-campaigned-and-voted-for-obama-518371298|title=Why 'Proud Republican' Sheryl Underwood Campaigned And Voted For Obama - AOL.com|first=|last=AOL|publisher=}}</ref> Underwood also campaigned for [[Hillary Clinton]] in the [[United States presidential election, 2016|2016 election]] "because we have to protect the legacy of President Obama. Low voter turnout benefits [[Donald Trump]] and the Republicans. He can't win."<ref>{{cite web|title=Sheryl Underwood Reveals What Republicans Don't Want Democrats To Know|url=https://blackamericaweb.com/2016/09/27/sheryl-underwood-reveals-what-republicans-dont-want-democrats-to-know/|work=BlackAmericaWeb.com|accessdate=1 March 2017}}</ref>
Underwood is a lifetime member of [[Zeta Phi Beta]] sorority, first joining in 1990.<ref name="MiamiImprov" /><ref name="ZetaPress" /> She served as president of the organization's Omicron Rho Zeta chapter, as the National Chair of Honorary Members, National Executive Board Chair and International Grand Basileus.<ref name="ZetaPress" /> She also chartered a graduate chapter of Zeta Phi Beta in [[Inglewood, California]].{{Citation needed|date=August 2008}}
In addition to the Zeta Phi Beta sorority, Underwood is also a member of the National Council of Negro Women and the NAACP.<ref name="MiamiImprov" /> She also founded the African-American Female Comedian Association.<ref name="MiamiImprov" />
In the fall of 2011, Underwood revealed that after dating seven years, her husband—who might have suffered from clinical depression—committed suicide after they had been married three years.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://theybf.com/2011/09/06/tv-fab-sheryl-underwood-debuts-on-the-talk-reveals-her-husbands-suicide |title=Sheryl Underwood Debuts on CBS ''The Talk'', Reveals Her Husband's Suicide}}</ref>
===Zeta Phi Beta presidency=== Underwood was elected as the 23rd International Grand Basileus (President) during Zeta Phi Beta's biennial business meeting in [[Las Vegas, Nevada]] in 2008. Her election as Grand Basileus was disputed, but District of Columbia Superior Court Judge Gerald I. Fisher dismissed a lawsuit against the sorority and Underwood that asked the court to unseat her.<ref name="ZetaPress">{{cite web|url=http://www.zphib1920.org/NewPres.html |title=Zeta Phi Beta Sorority, Incorporated Elects Entertainer Sheryl Underwood 23rd International President |date=2008-07-07 |publisher=Zeta Phi Beta Sorority, Inc. |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080821085905/http://www.zphib1920.org/NewPres.html |archivedate=2008-08-21 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/08/15/AR2008081502589.html|title=Comedian Fights to Retain Presidency of Sorority|date=2008-08-16|accessdate=2008-08-19|last=Alexander|first=Keith L.|work=washingtonpost.com|publisher=The Washington Post Company}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mercurynews.com/news/ci_11073048|title=Judge rules in favor of comedian in sorority|publisher=The Associated Press|work=San Jose Mercury News|date=2008-11-25|accessdate=2009-02-03}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> Her election made her the first professional entertainer to hold the highest elected office of a [[National Pan-Hellenic Council]] organization.{{Citation needed|date=February 2009}}
